docs.abstract: A Russian aluminum giant got a break that had eluded most others. Then it unraveled after Commerce officials realized it had been granted in error.
docs.snippet: A Russian aluminum giant got a break that had eluded most others. Then it unraveled after Commerce officials realized it had been granted in error.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Hundreds of companies have asked the Trump administration for a special break from its sweeping aluminum tariffs. Few have succeeded. One that managed to get an exemption is a Russian firm currently subject to Treasury Department sanctions.

headline.main: How a Blacklisted Russian Firm Won (and Lost) a Break From Trump’s Tariffs
headline.print_headline: Not So Fast: Putin Ally Loses Tariff Exemption

keywords.name: subject
keywords.value: Russian Interference in 2016 US Elections and Ties to Trump Associates

docs.abstract: President Trump has taken an interest in the F.B.I. headquarters, which had been set for redevelopment. Democrats wonder if he is trying to protect his hotel.
docs.snippet: President Trump has taken an interest in the F.B.I. headquarters, which had been set for redevelopment. Democrats wonder if he is trying to protect his hotel.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Nearly two years before he would begin his presidential campaign, Donald J. Trump arrived in Washington to show off his plans for a luxury hotel on Pennsylvania Avenue under a deal he had reached to lease the site from the General Services Administration.

headline.main: Trump’s Focus on a Washington Building Project Draws Scrutiny
headline.print_headline: Trump’s Interest in Long-Debated F.B.I. Building Project Draws Scrutiny

docs.abstract: States and advocacy groups challenging a change to the census form said Wilbur Ross’s shifting rationales required his testimony.
docs.snippet: States and advocacy groups challenging a change to the census form said Wilbur Ross’s shifting rationales required his testimony.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court temporarily blocked a court order on Monday that would have required Wilbur Ross, the secretary of commerce, to give a deposition in a lawsuit challenging the addition of a question concerning citizenship to the 2020 census.

headline.main: Supreme Court Blocks Wilbur Ross Deposition on Census Citizenship Question
headline.print_headline: Justices Block Ross Deposition on Census

docs.abstract: The police said the man, who was unarmed, appeared irate at the time of the shooting, stoking renewed fears of journalists being targeted in a polarized environment.
docs.snippet: The police said the man, who was unarmed, appeared irate at the time of the shooting, stoking renewed fears of journalists being targeted in a polarized environment.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A security guard shot and wounded a man who forced his way into a local television station, the police said Monday, stoking renewed fears that journalists have become targets in a highly polarized political environment.

headline.main: Guard Shoots Man Who Forced His Way Into Washington TV Station
headline.print_headline: Guard Shoots Trespasser At TV Station

docs.abstract: Two years ago they called each other “liar” and “sniveling coward.” But with midterm elections just two weeks away, President Trump traveled to Texas to campaign for Senator Ted Cruz.
docs.snippet: Two years ago they called each other “liar” and “sniveling coward.” But with midterm elections just two weeks away, President Trump traveled to Texas to campaign for Senator Ted Cruz.
docs.lead_paragraph: HOUSTON — While competing for the Republican presidential nomination in 2016, Donald J. Trump posed a biting question to voters: “Why would the people of Texas support Ted Cruz when he has accomplished absolutely nothing for them?”

headline.main: Trump and Cruz Put Aside Vitriol to Present a United Front
headline.print_headline: President Campaigns for the Man He Once Called ‘a Maniac’

docs.abstract: The C.I.A. director is helping the Turkish government with its inquiry into the killing of Jamal Khashoggi, and the Treasury secretary held a wide-ranging meeting with the Saudi crown prince.
docs.snippet: The C.I.A. director is helping the Turkish government with its inquiry into the killing of Jamal Khashoggi, and the Treasury secretary held a wide-ranging meeting with the Saudi crown prince.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration, confronted with further evidence of a cover-up in the killing of the journalist Jamal Khashoggi, veered on Monday between defending the value of its alliance with Saudi Arabia and pressing the Saudi government for answers.

headline.main: On Jamal Khashoggi Killing, Trump Administration Sends Mixed Signals
headline.print_headline: U.S. Sends Mixed Signs on Killing and Arab Ally

byline.original: By Mark Landler and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: Trump’s decision to dump a missile-control treaty seems to end an important period of arms control — which did not include China. But Europe is not happy.
docs.snippet: Trump’s decision to dump a missile-control treaty seems to end an important period of arms control — which did not include China. But Europe is not happy.
docs.lead_paragraph: Over the past few days the shape of what many in Europe and the United States call a new Cold War has begun to emerge — with threats and nuclear weapons that resemble the old one, punctuated by new dynamics, in part because of the rise of a rich, expanding and nationalist China.

headline.main: Trump May Revive the Cold War, but China Could Change the Dynamics
headline.print_headline: Trump May Revive Cold War, but China Could Change Dynamics

byline.original: By David E. Sanger and Steven Erlanger

docs.abstract: Theodore Frank, a critic of class action settlements, will argue his own case. On the whole, people representing themselves in the Supreme Court have done rather well.
docs.snippet: Theodore Frank, a critic of class action settlements, will argue his own case. On the whole, people representing themselves in the Supreme Court have done rather well.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Theodore H. Frank is familiar with the adage that a lawyer who represents himself has a fool for a client. But later this month, he will stand before the Supreme Court to argue his own case.

headline.main: His Case Made It to the Supreme Court. He Didn’t Have to Look Far for a Lawyer.
headline.print_headline: He Didn’t Have to Look Far For Someone to Argue His Case

docs.abstract: Rushan Abbas, a Uighur American business consultant, hopes to get her sister and aunt freed from Chinese detention by swaying United States policy.
docs.snippet: Rushan Abbas, a Uighur American business consultant, hopes to get her sister and aunt freed from Chinese detention by swaying United States policy.
docs.lead_paragraph: ROSSLYN, Va. — Speaking last month at a Washington think tank, Rushan Abbas relayed tales of suffering she had heard about China’s repression of ethnic Uighur Muslims — including the detention of members of her husband’s family in a widespread system of mass internment camps.

headline.main: Uighur Americans Speak Against China’s Internment Camps. Their Relatives Disappear.
headline.print_headline: Uighur Americans Criticize China. Relatives Vanish.

docs.abstract: The president has raised $106 million for his re-election, leading some Republicans to grumble that he is siphoning money from endangered congressional candidates.
docs.snippet: The president has raised $106 million for his re-election, leading some Republicans to grumble that he is siphoning money from endangered congressional candidates.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Donald J. Trump’s first campaign finance report in July 2015 revealed a shoestring operation run by a handful of loyalists working from a two-room suite in Trump Tower and funded almost entirely by $1.8 million in loans from the candidate.

headline.main: As Other Republican Candidates Struggle Financially, Trump Stockpiles Cash
headline.print_headline: Money Is Rolling In, but for the President, Not Vulnerable Republicans
